      '<p><strong>HOW MANY BEERS CAN YOU CARRY AT ONCE?</strong></p><p>If you’re using Corona’s innovative can design, you can easily stack and carry enough to serve you and 6 to 10 of your friends. Or, I suppose, enough cans to ensure a terrible next day for yourself. Whatever the case, you don’t need plastic rings for the cans or even a bag to carry them home (depending on your local open carry laws). The tops of each can interlock with the bottoms, creating a type of hipster beer sword.</p><p>This is just one way Grupo Modelo, the makers of Corona, are experimenting to be more earth-friendly with their products. They’ve even toyed with a plastic-free, plant-based biodegradable ring to hold your drinks together.</p><p><strong>WHERE CAN YOU GET THESE CANS?</strong></p><p>This inventive LEGO-can design isn’t available everywhere yet, so you won’t find it on the shelves of your local beer provider. But, the higher-ups in Grupo Modelo are committed to the environment, so you’ll be able to wave your ginormous staff of beer in the not-too-distant-future. They are so committed to being earth-conscious, that Carlos Ranero, marketing vice-president of Grupo Modelo’s parent company Anheuser-Busch InBev, stated that this can design will be freely available to anyone who wants to use it.</p><p><strong>THOUGHTFUL DESIGN INNOVATION</strong></p><p style="text-align: start">The Corona “Fit Packs” are an excellent example of thoughtful design innovation that is not only functional but also responsible.</p><p style="text-align: start">If you are looking for ways to better understand metal packaging, distribution, or even packaging design, you need to consider investing in our<span style="color: rgb(100, 116, 139)"> </span><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://packagingschool.com/certificates/">Certificate of Packaging Science</a><span style="color: rgb(100, 116, 139)">.</span></p>',
