      '<p>Have you ever heard of the <em>Savanna Preference</em>?</p><p>Our Founder and a Professor of Packaging Science at Clemson University, <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/drandrewhurley/">Dr. Andrew Hurley</a>, wrote for <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.packworld.com/home/article/21095539/designing-for-kids-stick-it-on-a-savanna">Packaging World</a> recently in an article titled, "Designing for Kids? Stick it on a Savanna!"</p><p>Dr. Hurley covers the savanna preference and uncovers studies that have indicated that, "<em>Children, as well as adults, are naturally drawn to prefer open, savanna-type landscapes. As package designers, we should take advantage of that</em>."</p><p><strong>Dr. Hurley stated</strong>:</p><blockquote><p>Surprising? Probably not. It makes sense that adults would prefer a savanna-type environment. Consumers want to get away from everyday hecticness and just relax and not have to think about things quite so hard.</p><p>So, we should design packages that encourage their brains to sigh in contentment when they look at them. If looking at a package makes them smile in relief, then the enclosed product may be perceived as more appealing and have a higher probability of purchase.</p><p>The preference for savanna environments is inherently stronger in children.</p></blockquote><p>Learn more about how to utilize the savanna preference to make effective packaging in the full article here: <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.packworld.com/home/article/21095539/designing-for-kids-stick-it-on-a-savanna">https://www.packworld.com/home/article/21095539/designing-for-kids-stick-it-on-a-savanna</a>.</p><p></p><h3 class="font-bold" style="text-align: start">LEARN MORE ABOUT PACKAGING DESIGN</h3><p style="text-align: start">Here at the Packaging School, we have a collection of online packaging design courses designed <em>by</em> packaging professionals <em>for</em> packaging professionals!</p><p style="text-align: start"><strong>Our suite of packaging design courses include:</strong></p><ul><li><p><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://packagingschool.com/courses/packaging-design-workflow">Packaging Design Workflow</a></p></li><li><p><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://packagingschool.com/courses/leveraging-human-factors-in-packaging-design">Leveraging Human Factors in Packaging Design</a></p></li><li><p><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://packagingschool.com/courses/introduction-to-corrugated-design">Intro to Corrugated Design</a></p></li><li><p><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://packagingschool.com/courses/package-printing">Package Printing</a></p></li></ul><p style="text-align: start">We also have a collection of packaging design videos on our <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.youtube.com/@Packagingschool">YouTube</a> channel, including our most popular video to date—<a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://youtu.be/euacI5VTBhY?si=vidPR70DR5tIS6my">How Package Design Affects Sales</a>.</p>',
