      '<p>\n  Many public companies have set aggressive sustainability targets; most of\n  which involve packaging. Now, more than ever, product companies are investing\n  in reducing the environmental impacts of their packaging and communicating\n  these efforts on their labels.\n</p>\n<p>\n  A major component to understanding your environmental impact is the amount of\n  production and discharge of carbon. So, many companies are asking the question\n  “How do we make carbon neutral packaging?”\n</p>\n<p>\n  This is a dense topic, so&nbsp;<a\n    href="/lessons/carbon-neutral-part-2"\n    rel="noopener noreferrer"\n    target="_blank"\n    ><strong>we will be back next month</strong></a\n  >&nbsp;with part two, implementation and measurement, of our study of carbon\n  neutrality.\n</p>\n<h2><strong>Optimize Your Sustainability Packaging Process</strong></h2>\n<p>\n  For a deeper dive into sustainability as it relates to packaging and ways to\n  reduce a company’s environmental footprint, look no further than our&nbsp;<a\n    href="https://packagingschool.com/sustainable-packaging/"\n    rel="noopener noreferrer"\n    target="_blank"\n    >sustainability course&nbsp;</a\n  >containing over 4 hours of engaging content.\n</p>\n<p>\n  While you are at it, check out our certificate programs,&nbsp;<a\n    href="https://packagingschool.com/get-to-know-cps/"\n    rel="noopener noreferrer"\n    target="_blank"\n    >Certificate of Packaging Science</a\n  >&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a\n    href="https://packagingschool.com/get-to-know-cmpm/"\n    rel="noopener noreferrer"\n    target="_blank"\n    >Certificate of Mastery in Packaging Management</a\n  >&nbsp;that cover this course andmuch more.\n</p>',
